He travelled to Lapland (1904, 1905, 1922), Kainuu (1902), Ingria (1903, 1906), Karelia (1902, 1905), and Estonia (1930).
Launis earned a Ph. D (1911) and was full professor at the University of Helsinki where he taught musical analysis and composition.
Deeply concerned with the availability of musical education for everyone, Launis founded and until 1930 directed the first popular conservatories in Finland, which still exist.
As early as 1920, Launis received a life pension from the Finnish State, with the permission to live abroad.
In 1930 Launis settled permanently in Nice, France, and lived there the remainder of his life.
